Claims CLAIMS  What is claimed is: 1. A method of analyzing a rock sample, comprising: analyzing one or more large-area, low-resolution micrographs of the rock sample obtained with large-area, low-resolution microscopy and identifying and geo- locating areas requiring higher-resolution imaging; selecting one or more analysis regions from the areas requiring higher-resolution imaging; using multi-spectral imaging on the one or more analysis regions and thereby obtaining a corresponding one or more high-resolution, multi-spectral images; and identifying one or more features of the rock sample from the corresponding one or more high-resolution, multi-spectral images. 2. The method of claim 1, wherein analyzing the one or more large-area, low-resolution micrographs is preceded by: identifying and selecting one or more key regions of the rock sample based on one or more attributes of the rock sample; and analyzing one or more optical thin sections of the rock sample with the large-area, low- resolution microscopy and thereby obtaining the one or more low-scale micrographs. 3. The method of claim 1 or 2, wherein the low-resolution microscopy comprises at least one of optical microscopy and low-magnitude backscatter electron microscopy. 4. The method of any one of claims 1 to 3, wherein selecting the one or more analysis regions further comprises selecting a multi-spectral imaging method based on at least one of a desired image resolution, a time required to obtain the desired image resolution, and a maximum data set size. 5. The method of claim 4, wherein the multi-spectral imaging method is selected from the group consisting of high-resolution backscattered electron imaging, energy dispersive x-ray spectroscopy, wavelength dispersive x-ray spectroscopy, high resolution x-ray fine structure spectroscopy, spectrally-resolved cathodoluminescence, pana-chromatic cathodoluminescent imaging, secondary electron imaging, energy -filtered secondary or backscattered electron imaging, angle-resolved electron imaging, magnetic domain imaging, electron-induced acoustic imaging, electron beam induced charge imaging, electron diffraction based imaging, electron-induced infrared imaging, fourier- 

 transform infrared spectroscopy, ultraviolet imaging, atomic force microscopy imaging, and acoustic microscopy imaging. 6. The method of claim 4 or 5, wherein selecting the multi-spectral imaging method includes selecting a sequential order of analysis and is further based on a consideration of potential physical damage of the rock sample by prolonged exposure to electron beams. 7. The method of any one of claims 1 to 6, wherein the one or more features of the rock sample are selected from the group consisting of grain shape, grain size, grain location, porosity, intervening cements, composition of pore lining materials, mineralogy, mineral fabric, and any combination thereof. 8. The method of any one of claims 1 to 7, wherein the multi-spectral imaging comprises cathodoluminescence and the method further comprises: obtaining a cathodoluminescent image; identifying from the cathodluminescent image a property selected from the group consisting of grain origin, cement type, chemistry, and porosity; and displaying the property using one or more colors or with gray scale intensity. 9. The method of any one of claims 1 to 8, wherein identifying the one or more features of the rock sample is automated using a computer programmed to identify the one or more features of the rock sample. 10. The method of any one of claims 1 to 9, further comprising upscaling the corresponding one or more high-resolution, multi-spectral images and thereby geo-locating the one or more features of the rock sample to the one or more key regions of the rock sample. 11. The method of claim 10, wherein upscaling the corresponding one or more high- resolution, multi-spectral images is automated with a computer. 12. The method of any one of claims 1 to 11, further comprising conducting a downhole hydraulic fracturing operation based on identification of the one or more features of the rock sample. 13. An apparatus, comprising: one or more processors; and a memory having embodied thereon processor executable instructions that, when executed by the one or more processors, cause the apparatus to: identify and select one or more key regions of a rock sample based on one or more attributes of the rock sample; 

 analyze one or more optical thin sections of the rock sample with large- area, low resolution microscopy and thereby obtain one or more large-area, low-resolution micrographs; analyze the one or more large-area, low-resolution micrographs and identifying areas requiring higher-resolution imaging; select one or more analysis regions from the areas requiring higher- resolution imaging; use multi-spectral imaging on the one or more analysis regions and thereby obtain a corresponding one or more high-resolution, multi-spectral images; and identify one or more features of the rock sample from the corresponding one or more high-resolution, multi-spectral images. 14. The apparatus of claim 13, wherein the large-area, low-resolution microscopy comprises at least one of optical microscopy and low-magnitude backscatter electron microscopy. 15. The apparatus of claim 13 or 14, wherein the processor executable instructions that, when executed by the one or more processors, cause the apparatus to select one or more analysis regions, further comprises causing the processor to select a multi-spectral imaging method based on at least one of a desired image resolution, a time required to obtain the desired image resolution, and a maximum data set size. 16. The apparatus of any one of claims 13 to 15, wherein the multi-spectral imaging method is selected from the group consisting of high-resolution backscattered electron imaging, energy dispersive x-ray spectroscopy, wavelength dispersive x-ray spectroscopy, high resolution x-ray fine structure spectroscopy, spectrally-resolved cathodoluminescence, pana-chromatic cathodoluminescent imaging, secondary electron imaging, energy- filtered secondary or backscattered electron imaging, angle-resolved electron imaging, magnetic domain imaging, electron-induced acoustic imaging, electron beam induced charge imaging, electron diffraction based imaging, electron-induced infrared imaging, fourier-transform infrared spectroscopy, ultraviolet imaging, atomic force microscopy imaging, and acoustic microscopy imaging. 17. The apparatus of any one of claims 13 to 16, wherein the one or more features of the rock sample are selected from the group consisting of grain shape, grain size, grain location, porosity, intervening cements, composition of pore lining materials, mineralogy, mineral fabric, and any combination thereof. 18. The apparatus of any one of claims 13 to 17, wherein the multi-spectral imaging comprises cathodoluminescence and wherein the processor executable instructions further cause the apparatus to: obtain a cathodoluminescent image; identify from the cathodluminescent image a property selected from the group consisting of grain origin, cement type, chemistry, and porosity; and display the property using one or more colors or with gray scale. 19. The apparatus of any one of claims 13 to 18, wherein the processor executable instructions further cause the apparatus to upscale the corresponding one or more high- resolution, multi-spectral images and thereby geo-locate the one or more features of the rock sample to the one or more key regions of the rock sample. 20. The apparatus of any one of claims 13 to 19, wherein the processor executable instructions that, when executed by the one or more processors, cause the apparatus to analyze the one or more large-area, low-resolution micrographs further comprises causing the processor to identify large-scale texture components.
